  <appendix xml:id="SageMath">
    <title>Computations using SageMath</title>
    <introduction>
      <p>
        We use online computer algebra system <url href="https://www.sagemath.org/">SageMath</url> to perform certain computations. It may be a useful tool to check the correctness of calculations. Please first do the calculations yourself and then verify using SageMath. 
      </p>
    </introduction>    
    <section xml:id="sec-sage-echelon-form">
      <title>Row reduced echelon form and a system of linear equations</title>
      <introduction>
        We use online computer algebra system <url href="https://www.sagemath.org/">SageMath</url> to compute the row reduced echelon form of a given matrix. In the following example <c>A=matrix(RR,[[1,2,1,-1],[9,7,5,5],[1,-2,2,8]])</c> represents <m>3\times 4</m> matrix <m>A</m> over <m>\R</m>. The entries <c>[1,2,1,-1]</c>, <c>[9,7,5,5]</c>, and <c>[1,-2,2,8]</c> represents the first, the second, and the third row of <m>A</m>, respectively.
      </introduction>
      <p>
        You may input the matrix of your choice to get the row reduced echelon form. Please first do the calculations yourself and then verify using SageMath.
      </p>
      <p>
        <sage>
        <input>
          sage: A=matrix(RR,[[1,2,1,-1],[9,7,5,5],[1,-2,2,8]]); A
          sage: A.echelon_form()
        </input>
      </sage>
      </p>
    
      <p>
        In the following SageMath can compute the solution of the system <m>AX=Y</m>. You may change <m>A</m> and <m>Y</m> appropriately.
    
        <sage>
          <input>
            sage: A=matrix(RR,[[1,0,0],[1,0,1],[2,2,1]])
            sage: Y=vector([1,0,0])
            sage: X = A.solve_right(Y)
            sage: A*X
            <!--sage: A*x==vector([1,0,0])-->
          </input>			
        </sage>
      </p>
    
      <p>
        In the following we can reduced the augmented matrix <m>[A|v]</m> to the row reduced echelon form. You may change <m>A</m> and <m>v</m> appropriately.
      <sage>
        <input>
          sage: A=matrix(RR,[[1,2,3],[1,0,1],[2,2,1]])
          sage: v=vector([1,0,0])
          sage: matrix(A.augment(v)).rref()
        </input>
      </sage>
      </p>
    </section>
    <section xml:id="sec-sage-rank-trace-det">
      <title>Computing rank, trace, and determinant</title>
      <introduction>
        We use online computer algebra system <url href="https://www.sagemath.org/">SageMath</url> to compute the rank, the trace and the determinant of a given matrix. In the following example <c>A=matrix(RR,[[1,2,0,-1],[1,6,0,1],[1,-2,2,8]])</c> represents <m>3\times 4</m> matrix <m>A</m> over <m>\R</m>. The entries <c>[1,2,0,-1]</c>, <c>[1,6,0,1]</c>, and <c>[1,-2,2,8]</c> represents the first, the second, and the third row of <m>A</m>, respectively.
      </introduction>
      <p>
        We can compute the rank of a matrix.
      </p>
      <sage>
        <input>
          sage: A=matrix(RR,[[1,2,0,-1],[1,6,0,1],[1,-2,2,8]])
          sage: A.rank()
        </input>
        <output>
          (for static output)
        </output>
      </sage>
      <p>
        We can compute the trace of a matrix.
      </p>
      <sage>
        <input>
          sage: A=matrix(RR,[[1,-1,1],[0,1,0],[0,0,-1]])
          sage: A.trace()
        </input>
        <output>
          (for static output)
        </output>
      </sage>
      <p>
        We can compute the determinant of a matrix.
      </p>
      <sage>
        <input>
          sage: A=matrix([[2,-1,0,0,0,0],[-1,2,-1,0,0,0],[0,-1,2,-1,0,0],[0,0,-1,2,-1,0],[0,0,0,-1,2,-1],[0,0,0,0,-1,2]])
          sage: A.det()
        </input>
        <output>
          (for static output)
        </output>
      </sage>
      
    </section>
